Visualization Analysis

The purpose of this component of the project is to analyze variables and look for trends or factors that may impact player and team performance in basketball. Exploration of data is more focused on in this component than in-depth analysis, which will be focused on in later components that rely on the findings in this component.

The histograms and bar charts above show that the San Antonio Spurs have a roughly larger average of field goals made while also more wins than Utah Jazz. To further explore how field goals made are associated with wins, a 95% confidence interval for the difference in mean field goals made is computed by bootstrapping 1000 resamples from all 49 NBA games during 2010-2024 with San Antonio Spurs and Utah Jazz as the matchup.


winning_games<-regular_season_totals|>filter(WL=="W")
losing_games<-regular_season_totals|>filter(WL=="L")

combined_games<-merge(winning_games,losing_games,by="gameId")|>mutate(diffFieldGoalsMade=fieldGoalsMade.x-fieldGoalsMade.y)

sas_uta_games<-filter(combined_games,(teamName.x=="San Antonio Spurs" & teamName.y=="Utah Jazz") | (teamName.x=="Utah Jazz" & teamName.y=="San Antonio Spurs"))

sas_uta_field_goals_bootstrap_distribution<-sas_uta_games|>specify(response=diffFieldGoalsMade)|>generate(reps=1000,type="bootstrap")|>calculate(stat="mean")

sas_uta_percentile_confidence_interval<-sas_uta_field_goals_bootstrap_distribution|>get_confidence_interval(level=0.95,type="percentile")

sas_uta_field_goals_confidence_interval<-visualize(sas_uta_field_goals_bootstrap_distribution)+shade_confidence_interval(endpoints=sas_uta_percentile_confidence_interval) +
                                 labs(x="Difference in Mean Field Goals Made",title="Bootstrap Sampling Distribution for Mean Difference in Field Goals Made for San Antonio Spurs vs. Utah Jazz (n=1000)")

sas_uta_field_goals_confidence_interval

sas_uta_percentile_confidence_interval

Based on the interval, 95% of sample sizes of 49 games will produce a 95% confidence interval that contains the true mean difference in field goals made betwen the San Antonio Spurs and Utah Jazz. In other words, there is 95% confidence that the true mean difference in field goals made between the San Antonio Spurs and Utah Jazz lies between approximately 1.73 and 4.49 field goals. Given that the interval ranges above a 1.5 difference in field goals made, such phenomenon further supports the suggestion that field goals made are a key factor to winning basketball games. To further explore this suggestion, a 95% confidence interval is computed for the entire sample of NBA games.

field_goals_bootstrap_distribution<-combined_games|>specify(response=diffFieldGoalsMade)|>generate(reps=1000,type="bootstrap")|>calculate(stat="mean")

percentile_confidence_interval<-field_goals_bootstrap_distribution|>get_confidence_interval(level=0.95,type="percentile")

field_goals_confidence_interval<-visualize(field_goals_bootstrap_distribution)+shade_confidence_interval(endpoints=percentile_confidence_interval) +
                                 labs(x="Difference in Mean Field Goals Made",title="Bootstrap Sampling Distribution for Difference in Mean Field Goals Made (n=1000)")

field_goals_confidence_interval

percentile_confidence_interval

The results from building a 95% confidence interval for the mean difference in field goals made on the entire sample further supports the suggestion that field goals made are essential to success in basketball games as the confidence interval ranges from approximately 3.89 to 4.03 games. Not only does the lower bound take on a larger difference in field goals made, but the entire interval is narrower, which indicates more precision. The increased precision is expected as the sample size is 16658.

df <- 16658  # degrees of freedom

x <- seq(-4, 4, length.out = 1000)  # x-axis values covering typical range
y <- dt(x, df = df)  # t-distribution density values

plot(x, y, type = "l", lwd = 2, col = "blue",
     main = paste("t-distribution with", df, "degrees of freedom"),
     ylab = "Density", xlab = "t")

ggplot(z, aes(x = diff)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50, fill = "lightblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(z$diff), color = "blue", size = 1.2) +   # sample mean

  theme_minimal()
mean_diff <- mean(z$diff)
sd_diff <- sd(z$diff)
n <- length(z$diff)
se_diff <- sd_diff / sqrt(n)

z_star <- qnorm(0.975)
lower <- mean_diff - z_star * se_diff
upper <- mean_diff + z_star * se_diff

ggplot(z, aes(x = diff)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50, fill = "lightblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean_diff, color = "blue", size = 1.2, linetype = "solid") +    # mean line
  geom_vline(xintercept = lower, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +                   # lower CI
  geom_vline(xintercept = upper, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +                   # upper CI
  labs(title = "Histogram of Differences with 95% Confidence Interval for the Mean",

       y = "Count") +

mean_estimate <- 10
standard_error <- 2
conf_level <- 0.95
alpha <- 1 - conf_level

# Critical z-value
z <- qnorm(1 - alpha/2)

# Confidence interval limits
lower <- mean_estimate - z * standard_error
upper <- mean_estimate + z * standard_error


df <- data.frame(
